1
00:00:30,960 --> 00:00:34,170
The Antarctic continent is the highest,
windiest,

2
00:00:34,170 --> 00:00:38,280
driest and coldest continent in the
world. It contains around ninety percent

3
00:00:38,280 --> 00:00:42,420
of the world's ice and thereby seventy percent of the
world's fresh water

4
00:00:42,460 --> 00:00:45,100
 and is home to giant active volcanoes

5
00:00:45,100 --> 00:00:49,460
enormous subglacial lakes and rocks over
four billion years old

6
00:00:53,930 --> 00:00:57,040
It is one of the few places in the world
that has never seen a war

7
00:00:57,040 --> 00:01:01,049
where the environment is fully protected
and science has priority

8
00:01:01,049 --> 00:01:06,689
The coast of Antarctica is dotted with
research stations from over 40 different countries

9
00:01:06,689 --> 00:01:09,740
and is home to an international community
of scientists

10
00:01:09,740 --> 00:01:14,869
some of whom are stationed on the
continent all year round

11
00:01:14,869 --> 00:01:19,920
The interior of Antarctica is a vast
expanse of ice

12
00:01:19,920 --> 00:01:26,420
in some places four kilometres thick. The
continent's divided in two by the Transantarctic mountains

13
00:01:26,430 --> 00:01:29,610
high up on the polar plateau of east
antarctica

14
00:01:29,610 --> 00:01:35,950
lies the South Pole, the goal of the
majority of tourism and expeditions that happens in the continent

15
00:01:36,060 --> 00:01:39,700
It is the location of a giant US science base

16
00:01:46,649 --> 00:01:50,320
These are the Ellsworth mountains in
West Antarctica

17
00:01:50,320 --> 00:01:53,579
The highest mountain range in the whole
continent

18
00:01:53,579 --> 00:01:57,829
They consist of the northern Sentinel
range and the Southern heritage range

19
00:01:57,829 --> 00:02:02,819
The Heritage range is home to numerous
glaciers that flow down from the West Antarctic Plateau

20
00:02:02,819 --> 00:02:07,990
One of which is called Union glacier, it is a large heavy crevassed glacier

21
00:02:08,709 --> 00:02:11,750
86 kilometers long and nine kilometres
wide

22
00:02:11,750 --> 00:02:15,270
and is the site and Union glacier camp

23
00:02:17,110 --> 00:02:20,240
The camp is operated by Antarctic
Logistics and Expeditions

24
00:02:20,240 --> 00:02:24,460
and is open for three months during the
Antarctic summer

25
00:02:24,500 --> 00:02:27,420
It's situated near Union glacier blue ice runway

26
00:02:27,420 --> 00:02:30,140
A naturally-occurring stretch of blue ice

27
00:02:30,900 --> 00:02:34,459
ALE uses various types of aircraft
to operate in Antarctica 

28
00:02:34,459 --> 00:02:38,400
A large Russian Ilyushin jet runs
intercontinental flights from Chile

29
00:02:38,400 --> 00:02:43,140
and transports the majority of heavy
cargo and passengers to the camp

30
00:02:43,240 --> 00:02:48,340
 A Bassler BT 67 and two de Havilland Twin Otters are used to fly within Antarctic

31
00:02:48,349 --> 00:02:52,730
Both these aircraft are fitted with skis
and can land almost anywhere

32
00:02:52,730 --> 00:02:57,590
For three months each year Union glacier
camp acts as a logistics hub for

33
00:02:57,590 --> 00:02:58,449
scientists,

34
00:02:58,449 --> 00:02:59,480
tourists,

35
00:02:59,480 --> 00:03:00,280
South Pole teams,

36
00:03:00,340 --> 00:03:01,000
 and climbers

37
00:03:01,000 --> 00:03:04,480
And ALE provide support to both private expeditions

38
00:03:04,489 --> 00:03:06,929
and national Antarctic programs. 

39
00:03:06,980 --> 00:03:13,880
Every year movies are made, books written and stories
told of the expeditions that pass through the camp

40
00:03:13,890 --> 00:03:16,880
This film is about the people who play a
part in making that possible

41
00:03:16,880 --> 00:03:22,450
but in particular it is about the 10 people who
make up the Union glacier start-up crew

42
00:03:22,460 --> 00:03:24,110
The start-up crew are a small team

43
00:03:24,120 --> 00:03:30,160
that land in the pristine glacier ahead of
everybody else and a thousand kilometers from the nearest science base

44
